#Text=Arab
#Text=Arab ( pronounced AY-rab ) is a small town in North Alabama .
#Text=Get in
#Text=The best way to get in is to fly into the nearby airport in Huntsville and drive to Arab .

#Text=The main highways in and around Arab are US-231 , which runs north-south from Huntsville to Blountsville and Oneonta and has most of Arab 's chain stores and fast food restaurants ; and AL-69 , which runs east-west from Guntersville to Cullman through Arab and makes up the northern half of Main St , where most of Arab 's locally-owned small businesses are .
#Text=Get around
#Text=There is no public transportation so bring a car !
#Text=Parking is free and easy to find except during major events like the Poke Salat Festival .
#Text=Downtown is very small and can be explored easily by foot .
#Text=See

#Text=Arab City Park is beautiful and well maintained city park that includes the Arab historic park , which features several restored buildings dating from the late 1800s to the 1940s and exhibits depicting daily life in this part of the country during those times .
#Text=Thompson Falls is a beautiful and often impressive waterfall that lies on private property ( visitors welcome and expected , but be respectful ! ) a few miles outside of town .
#Text=If you 're heading south on Main St , you can get there by turning left past the Meat Market onto Fry Gap Rd .
#Text=Follow this road for a mile and make a slight left onto Brashie r 's Chapel Rd .

#Text=After 2.5 miles , turn right onto Thompson Falls Rd and after another 3/4ths of a mile , take a left onto Thompson Falls Dr. Past the second house on the left , you will see a gravel drive leading off into the woods .
#Text=This is the route down to the falls .
#Text=It is recommended to park on the side of the road and walk down .
#Text=Do
#Text=The Poke Salat Festival happens in downtown Arab on the third Saturday of every May .
#Text=The name refers to the folk term for a salad made from pokeweed , a toxic plant that requires special preparation to make it safe for consumption .
#Text=Buy
#Text=Walmart is located off of 231 on the north side of town .
#Text=Warehouse on the north side , and Foodland on the south are good places to get groceries for cheap .
#Text=The Spinning Groove on Main St is a local record store , and the owner makes great recommendations .
#Text=Eat
#Text=Most regional and national fast food chains have a presence in Arab along highway 231 .
#Text=Huddle House is the only one open overnight .

#Text=Local favorites include Midas Burger , known for their delicious chicken sauce , Milner 's Dairy Delight , Son 's Barbecue which serves mainly pulled pork , and L Rancho Cafe on Main St , the home of poke salat .
#Text=Tasty and decently priced Mexican food can be found at Los Arcos as well as Sierra 's .
#Text=The only option for Chinese is Panda III , which is in the same line of shops as Sierra 's and will probably compare unfavorably with the Chinese food you get in your hometown .
#Text=Drink
#Text=Arab only legalized the sale of alcohol fairly recently and as such drinking options are still fairly limited .
#Text=CJ 's Saloon on highway 69 has pool and attracts mostly an older crowd .
#Text=Jerzee 's is a sports bar on the north side of 231 .
#Text=Last call in Alabama is at 2am .
#Text=No alcohol is sold in Arab on Sundays , anywhere .
#Text=Beer and wine can be bought at regular retail stores , but liquor is only available at state-owned " ABC " stores .
#Text=Sleep
#Text=Quality Inn is located behind the McDonald 's off of 231 and has rooms for around $ 60 dollars a night .
#Text=The Arabian Motel , on Main St , and Green Park Motel , south of town on 231 , are cheaper and have mostly long-term residents and an unfavorable local reputation .
#Text=Connect
#Text=The Arab Public Library on Main St offers internet-connected computers for use by guests .
#Text=Walmart and most of the fast food places also allow customers to connect to wifi .
